{"id":"1909.09327","submitter":"Xue-Ke Song","authors":"Huan Yang, Zhi-Yong Ding, Dong Wang, Hao Yuan, Xue-Ke Song, Jie Yang,\n  Chang-Jin Zhang, and Liu Ye","title":"Experimental certification of steering criterion based on general\n  entropic uncertainty relation","comments":"6 pages, 3 figures, 4 tables, submitted to Phys. Rev. A on 19th\n  August, 2019 (Under review)","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 101, 022324 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.101.022324","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum steering describes the phenomenon that one system can be immediately\ninfluenced by another with local measurements. It can be detected by the\nviolation of a powerful and useful steering criterion from general entropic\nuncertainty relation. This criterion, in principle, can be evaluated\nstraightforwardly and achieved by only probability distributions from a finite\nset of measurement settings. Herein, we experimentally verify the steering\ncriterion by means of the two-photon Werner-like states and three Pauli\nmeasurements. The results indicate that quantum steering can be verified by the\ncriterion in a convenient way. In particular, it is no need to perform the\nusual quantum state tomography in experiment, which reduces the required\nexperimental resources greatly. Moreover, we demonstrate that the criterion is\nstronger than the linear one for the detecting quantum steering of the\nWerner-like states.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 Sep 2019 05:27:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-02-26"}
